{"title_page": "Gutin Mountains", "text_new": "[[File:Muntii Gutaiului - Harta 3D.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Gutin Mountains]]\nThe '''Gutin Mountains''' ({{Lang-ro|Mun\u021bii Gut\u00e2i}}; {{lang-hu|Gutin-hegys\u00e9g}}; {{lang-uk|\u0413\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0432}}) are a [[mountain range]] within the [[Vihorlat-Gutin Area]] of the [[Inner Eastern Carpathians]]. They are centered in [[Maramure\u0219 County]] in [[Romania]], bordering [[Satu Mare County]], and also stretching further towards northwest as the [[Oa\u0219 Mountains]], reaching border with [[Zakarpattia Oblast]] in [[Ukraine]].{{sfn|F\u00f6ldvary|1988|p=221-222}}\n\nIts highest mountain is [[Gut\u00e2i Peak]] (1443 m). The northern sections of Gutin Mountains contain the volcanic mountain chain ''Creasta Coco\u015fului'' (Cock's comb).\n\n==See also==\n[[File:Maramures.png|220px|thumb|right|[[Maramure\u0219 County]] in Romania]]\n[[Image:SM County Blank Map.gif|220px|thumb|right|[[Satu Mare County]] in Romania, with Gutin Mountains and [[Oa\u0219 Mountains]] located on its eastern and northern borders]]\n* [[Romanian Carpathians]]\n* [[Ukrainian Carpathians]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=F\u00f6ldvary|first=G\u00e1bor Z.|title=Geology of the Carpathian Region|year=1988|location=Singapore|publisher=World Scientific Publishing Company|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eAQ8DQAAQBAJ}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sacel-maramures.ro/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/HFMaramures-13.jpg Gutin Mountains on the geographical map of Maramure\u0219 County]\n* [https://sites.google.com/site/romanianatura1/home/relief-romania-muntii-carpati/carpatii-rasariteni-harti-marcaje-pesteri/oas/muntii-oasului.JPG Gutin and Oa\u0219 Mountains on the northern section map of the Satu Mare County]\n\n{{coord|47|41|48|N|23|50|27|E|region:RO_type:mountain_source:kolossus-huwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gutin Mountains}}\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of the Eastern Carpathians]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Romania]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Ukraine]]\n\n{{romania-geo-stub}}\n{{ukraine-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Muntii Gutaiului - Harta 3D.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Gutin Mountains]]\nThe '''Gutin Mountains''' ({{Lang-ro|Mun\u021bii Gut\u00e2i}}; {{lang-hu|Gutin-hegys\u00e9g}}; {{lang-uk|\u0413\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0432}}) are a [[mountain range]] within the [[Vihorlat-Gutin Area]] of the [[Inner Eastern Carpathians]]. They are centered in [[Maramure\u015f County]] in [[Romania]], bordering [[Satu Mare County]], and also stretching further towards northwest as the [[Oa\u0219 Mountains]], reaching border with [[Zakarpattia Oblast]] in [[Ukraine]].{{sfn|F\u00f6ldvary|1988|p=221-222}}\n\nIts highest mountain is [[Gut\u00e2i Peak]] (1443 m). The northern sections of Gutin Mountains contain the volcanic mountain chain ''Creasta Coco\u015fului'' (Cock's comb).\n\n==See also==\n[[File:Maramures.png|220px|thumb|right|[[Maramure\u015f County]] in Romania]]\n[[Image:SM County Blank Map.gif|220px|thumb|right|[[Satu Mare County]] in Romania, with Gutin Mountains and [[Oa\u0219 Mountains]] located on its eastern and northern borders]]\n* [[Romanian Carpathians]]\n* [[Ukrainian Carpathians]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=F\u00f6ldvary|first=G\u00e1bor Z.|title=Geology of the Carpathian Region|year=1988|location=Singapore|publisher=World Scientific Publishing Company|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eAQ8DQAAQBAJ}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sacel-maramures.ro/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/HFMaramures-13.jpg Gutin Mountains on the geographical map of Maramure\u015f County]\n* [https://sites.google.com/site/romanianatura1/home/relief-romania-muntii-carpati/carpatii-rasariteni-harti-marcaje-pesteri/oas/muntii-oasului.JPG Gutin and Oa\u0219 Mountains on the northern section map of the Satu Mare County]\n\n{{coord|47|41|48|N|23|50|27|E|region:RO_type:mountain_source:kolossus-huwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gutin Mountains}}\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of the Eastern Carpathians]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Romania]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Ukraine]]\n\n{{romania-geo-stub}}\n{{ukraine-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: Maramure\u015f County \u2192 Maramure\u0219 County (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gutin_Mountains"}
{"title_page": "GScube", "text_new": "The '''GScube''' was a hardware tool released by [[Sony]] intended for use in [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] production houses consisting of a custom variant of sixteen [[PlayStation 2]] motherboards [[parallel computing|running in parallel]]. The PlayStation 2 (PS2) is a video game console that was manufactured by Sony Computer Entertainment. It was released on March 4, 2000, in Japan followed by North America and Europe later the same year. It was unveiled that same year at [[SIGGRAPH]]; the name \"GSCube\" is short for [[Graphics Synthesizer]] Cube. It was used for two projects, [[Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within]] and the film incarnation of [[Resident Evil]].\n\nAccording to some sources{{fact|date=June 2015}}, they were all sent back to Sony in [[Japan]] and were subsequently dismantled. They were used for prototyping visual rendering in ''Final Fantasy'', ''[[The Matrix]]'' and ''[[Antz]]'', as well as in a [[flight simulator]]. Although the GSCube had good rendering capability, they had a major bottleneck in connecting to external computers to transfer content{{fact|date=June 2015}}.\n\n== Technical specifications ==\n* 16 &times; [[Emotion Engine]] CPUs clocked at 294.912&nbsp;MHz\n* 2&nbsp;GB of DRDRAM Rambus main memory (16 &times; 128&nbsp;MB)\n**(128&nbsp;MB was a common memory allocation on devkits vs.  the 32&nbsp;MB on shipping units)\n* Memory Bus Bandwidth 50.3&nbsp;GB/s (3.1&nbsp;GB/s &times; 16) \n* Floating Point Performance 97.5&nbsp;GFLOPS (6.1&nbsp;GFLOPS &times; 16)\n* 16 &times; \"[[Graphics Synthesizer]] \"I-32\" Graphics Processors clocked at 147.456&nbsp;MHz\n* 512&nbsp;MB of eDRAM Video Memory (16 &times; 32&nbsp;MB)\n**(The \"I-32\" Graphics Synthesizer was a custom variant that contained 32&nbsp;MB of eDRAM instead of the typical 4&nbsp;MB)\n* eDRAM Bandwidth 755&nbsp;GB/s (47.2&nbsp;GB/s &times; 16) \n* Pixel Fill Rate 37.7&nbsp;GB/s (2.36&nbsp;GB/s &times; 16)\n* Maximum Polygon Drawing Rate 1.2&nbsp;Gpolygons/s (73.7&nbsp;Mpolygons/s &times; 16)\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/9.05/gs3.html ''Wired'' article]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120322025655/http://techon.nikkeibp.co.jp/NEA/archive/200010/113496/ \"Nikkei Electronics\" article]\n* [http://ps2.ign.com/articles/082/082490p1.html \"IGN\" article]\n\n{{PlayStation}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gscubu}}\n[[Category:MIPS architecture]]\n[[Category:Sony products]]\n\n{{videogame-hardware-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''GScube''' was a hardware tool released by [[Sony]] intended for use in [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] production houses consisting of a custom variant of sixteen [[PlayStation 2]] motherboards [[parallel computing|running in parallel]]. The PlayStation 2 (PS2) is a video game console that was manufactured by Sony Computer Entertainment. It was released on March 4, 2000, in Japan followed by North America and Europe later the same year. It was unveiled that same year at [[SIGGRAPH]]; the name \"GSCube\" is short for [[Graphics Synthesizer]] Cube. It was used for two projects, [[Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within]] and the film incarnation of [[Resident Evil]].\n\nAccording to some sources{{fact|date=June 2015}}, they were all sent back to Sony in [[Japan]] and were subsequently dismantled. They were used for prototyping visual rendering in Final Fantasy, [[The Matrix]] and [[Antz]], as well as in a [[flight simulator]]. Although the GSCube had good rendering capability, they had a major bottleneck in connecting to external computers to transfer content{{fact|date=June 2015}}.\n\n== Technical specifications ==\n* 16 &times; [[Emotion Engine]] CPUs clocked at 294.912&nbsp;MHz\n* 2&nbsp;GB of DRDRAM Rambus main memory (16 &times; 128&nbsp;MB)\n**(128&nbsp;MB was a common memory allocation on devkits vs.  the 32&nbsp;MB on shipping units)\n* Memory Bus Bandwidth 50.3&nbsp;GB/s (3.1&nbsp;GB/s &times; 16) \n* Floating Point Performance 97.5&nbsp;GFLOPS (6.1&nbsp;GFLOPS &times; 16)\n* 16 &times; \"[[Graphics Synthesizer]] \"I-32\" Graphics Processors clocked at 147.456&nbsp;MHz\n* 512&nbsp;MB of eDRAM Video Memory (16 &times; 32&nbsp;MB)\n**(The \"I-32\" Graphics Synthesizer was a custom variant that contained 32&nbsp;MB of eDRAM instead of the typical 4&nbsp;MB)\n* eDRAM Bandwidth 755&nbsp;GB/s (47.2&nbsp;GB/s &times; 16) \n* Pixel Fill Rate 37.7&nbsp;GB/s (2.36&nbsp;GB/s &times; 16)\n* Maximum Polygon Drawing Rate 1.2&nbsp;Gpolygons/s (73.7&nbsp;Mpolygons/s &times; 16)\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/9.05/gs3.html ''Wired'' article]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120322025655/http://techon.nikkeibp.co.jp/NEA/archive/200010/113496/ \"Nikkei Electronics\" article]\n* [http://ps2.ign.com/articles/082/082490p1.html \"IGN\" article]\n\n{{PlayStation}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gscubu}}\n[[Category:MIPS architecture]]\n[[Category:Sony products]]\n\n{{videogame-hardware-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Frap", "label": "safe", "comment": "Italic", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GScube"}
{"title_page": "Mircea Sasu", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Mircea Sasu\n| image =\n| fullname = <!-- if different -->\n| birth_date = 5 October 1939\n| birth_place = [[:ro:Ferneziu|Ferneziu]], [[Maramure\u0219 County]], [[Romania]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1983|10|17|1939|10|05|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Romania]]\n| currentclub =\n| position = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n|  youthyears1 =   1955\u20131959 \n| youthyears2 =  1959\u20131960\n|  youthclubs1 =   Minerul Baia Mare \n| youthclubs2 =  Dinamo S\u0103sar\n|  years1 =   1960\u20131961 \n| years2 =  1961\u20131963 \n| years3 =  1963\u20131967 \n| years4 =  1967\u20131970 \n| years5 =  1970\u20131971 \n| years6 =  1971\u20131972\n|  clubs1 =   [[FC Dinamo Bucure\u015fti|Dinamo Bucure\u015fti]] \n| clubs2 =  [[UTA Arad]] \n| clubs3 =  [[Minerul Baia Mare]] \n| clubs4 =  [[Farul Constan\u0163a]] \n| clubs5 =  [[Fenerbah\u00e7e]] \n| clubs6 =  [[Minerul Baia Mare]]\n| caps1 =      7    \n| caps2 =   50   \n| caps3 =   95   \n| caps4 =   71   \n| caps5 =    7    \n| caps6 =   31   \n| goals1 =  2  \n| goals2 =  25  \n| goals3 =  34  \n| goals4 =  21  \n| goals5 =  4  \n| goals6 =  11 \n| nationalyears1 =   1963\u20131968\n| nationalteam1 =   [[Romanian national football team|Romania]]\n| nationalcaps1 =    9  \n| nationalgoals1 =   2 \n| manageryears1 =  \n| managerclubs1 =  \n| pcupdate = 26 December 2009\n| ntupdate = 26 December 2009\n}}\n\n'''Mircea Sasu''', (5 October 1939 \u2013 17 October 1983), was a [[Romania]]n football striker, who played for [[FC Baia Mare|Minerul Baia Mare]], [[UT Arad]], [[FC Dinamo Bucure\u015fti|Dinamo Bucharest]], [[Farul Constan\u0163a]] in Romania and [[Fenerbah\u00e7e SK]] in Turkey.\n\nHe was famous in [[Turkey]] for his freekick and direct corner goals.<ref>[http://blog.milliyet.com.tr/3-korner-1-penalti/Blog/?BlogNo=67313 3 Corner to 1 penalty]</ref>\n\n== Career statistics ==\n=== International goals ===\n{| class=\"wiki